colnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1226–about 1260":"1226–about 1260","1216–1230":"1216–1230","1226–1260":"1226–1260","–1286":"–1286","1228–1286":"1228–1286","1236–1286":"1236–1286","1196–1251":"1196–1251","about 1260":"about 1260","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1196":"1196","1260":"1260","1228":"1228","1216":"1216","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1236":"1236","Abt 1242":"about 1242",", Lincolnshire, , England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Gosberkirk, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Rea  .","English: topographic name for someone living at a place where rye (Old English <i>ryge</i>) was grown, or perhaps an occupational name for someone who grew or sold it.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads so named, most of them from Old Norse <i>rjóthr</i> ‘clearing in a forest’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ryer","meanings":["English (Sussex and Kent): probably from   Rye   (see   Rea  ) + the suffix <i>-er</i>, and is thus synonymous with Middle English <i>atte Rye</i>, denoting someone who lived by a river or an island. This type of formation is common in Sussex and Kent.","Americanized form of German   Reier   ‘heron’ or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rajar</b> or <b>Rajer</b> (see   Rayer  )."]},{"name":"Romney","meanings":["English: habitational name from Romney (Kent), from an uncertain first element (perhaps an Old English personal name <i>Rūmen</i>) + Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’. Compare   Rye   2."]},{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":33,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Rye was born in 1226, in Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Philip de Rye, was 30 and his mother, Kinna of Gosberton, was 31. He married *E ALICE MRS Robert de RYE in 1242, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1260, in Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1226–about 1260":"1226–umbes 1260","1216–1230":"1216–1230","1226–1260":"1226–1260","–1286":"–1286","1228–1286":"1228–1286","1236–1286":"1236–1286","1196–1251":"1196–1251","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1196":"1196","1260":"1260","1228":"1228","1216":"1216","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1236":"1236","Abt 1242":"umbes 1242",", Lincolnshire, , England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gosberkirk, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, I